赖 // ... // 创建ExcelWriter对象 ExcelWriter excelWriter = EasyExcel.write(\\"output.xlsx\\").build(); // 编写Excel文件内容 List<User> userList = getUserData(); // 获取用户数据列表 // 设置Excel表头 List<List<String>> head = new ArrayList<>(); head.add(Arrays.asList(\\"ID\\", \\"姓名\\", \\"年龄\\")); // 写入数据 excelWriter.write(userList, EasyExcel.writerSheet(\\"Sheet1\\").head(head).build()); // 设定样式或格式 // ... // 保存Excel文件 excelWriter.finish(); \`\`\` 注意，上述示例假设你已经有一个名为\`User\`的类来代表用户对象，\`getUserData\`方法返回一个包含用户数据的列表。 这只是EasyExcel导出文件的基本示例，你可以根据需要进行更多的定制，例如分Sheet导出、合并单元格、设定宽度等。可以查阅EasyExcel的文档来学习更多高级用法和功能。"},{"prompt":"For Minecraft Forge mod making for Minecraft 1.7.10, how do you use the OreDictionary when registering a crafting recipe?","completion":"To use the OreDictionary when registering a crafting recipe in Minecraft Forge for Minecraft 1.7.10, you can follow these steps: Step 1: Import the necessary classes \`\`\`java import net.minecraftforge.oredict.ShapedOreRecipe; import net.minecraft.item.crafting.IRecipe; import net.minecraft.item.ItemStack; import cpw.mods.fml.common.registry.GameRegistry; \`\`\` Step 2: Create a new ShapedOreRecipe object The ShapedOreRecipe class allows you to use OreDictionary entries in your recipe. Create a new instance of ShapedOreRecipe, passing the desired output ItemStack, followed by the recipe pattern and OreDictionary entries. \`\`\`java ItemStack output = new ItemStack(/* Your output item */); ShapedOreRecipe recipe = new ShapedOreRecipe(output, \\"ABC\\", \\"DEF\\", \\"GHI\\", 'A', /* Your OreDictionary entry or ItemStack for slot 'A' */, 'B', /* Your OreDictionary entry or ItemStack for slot 'B' */, // repeat for other slots... 'I', /* Your OreDictionary entry or ItemStack for slot 'I' */); \`\`\` Step 3: Register the recipe Finally, register the recipe using the GameRegistry class. \`\`\`java GameRegistry.addRecipe(recipe); \`\`\` Here's an example recipe that uses OreDictionary for two different item variations of wood blocks and a specific item in the center crafting slot: \`\`\`java import net.minecraftforge.oredict.ShapedOreRecipe; import net.minecraft.item.crafting.IRecipe; import net.minecraft.item.ItemStack; import cpw.mods.fml.common.registry.GameRegistry; public class MyModRecipes { public static void registerRecipes() { // Recipe with OreDictionary entries ItemStack output = new ItemStack(/* Your output item */); ShapedOreRecipe recipe = new ShapedOreRecipe(output, \\"ABA\\", \\"CDC\\", \\"AEA\\", 'A', \\"plankWood\\", // OreDictionary entry for any wood plank 'B', \\"logWood\\", // OreDictionary entry for any wood log 'C', new ItemStack(/* Your specific item */), 'D', new ItemStack(/* Another specific item */), 'E', new ItemStack(/* Yet another specific item */)); GameRegistry.addRecipe(recipe); } } \`\`\` Make sure to replace /* Your output item */, /* Your OreDictionary entry or ItemStack for slot 'A' */, and so on, with your actual item and OreDictionary entries. By using the OreDictionary in your crafting recipes, you can ensure that your mod will work with different variations of items that share the same OreDictionary entry, providing flexibility to the players using your mod."},{"prompt":"In versions prior to that, there was a method in the players' inventory called getDamageVsEntity. This has been completely removed, not just renamed, for 1.7.10 from what I see. What do you recommend using in it's place, without actually attacking the other entity?","completion":"In Minecraft 1.7.10, the \`getDamageVsEntity\` method in the player's inventory has indeed been removed. However, you can still calculate the damage a player would deal to another entity without actually attacking it by utilizing the \`AttributeModifier\` system in Minecraft Forge. Here's an example of how you can calculate damage using the player's held item and apply modifiers, similar to the old \`getDamageVsEntity\` method: \`\`\`java import net.minecraft.entity.SharedMonsterAttributes; import net.minecraft.entity.ai.attributes.AttributeModifier; import net.minecraft.entity.player.EntityPlayer; import net.minecraft.entity.player.EntityPlayerMP; import net.minecraft.item.ItemStack; import net.minecraft.util.DamageSource; import net.minecraftforge.common.ForgeHooks; public class MyModDamageUtils { public static float calculateDamage(EntityPlayer player, ItemStack heldItem, float baseDamage) { // Get the player's attack damage attribute double attackDamage = player.getEntityAttribute(SharedMonsterAttributes.attackDamage).getBaseValue(); // Optionally, apply any modifiers to the attack damage attribute attackDamage += player.getEntityAttribute(SharedMonsterAttributes.attackDamage) .getModifier(UUID.fromString(\\"your_modifier_uuid_here\\")).getAmount(); // Apply any additional custom logic or modifiers to the base damage value // Here you can factor in the held item's properties, enchantments, or any other custom calculations // For example, you can check the item's damage, enchantments, or any other properties if (!heldItem.isEmpty()) { ItemStack copy = heldItem.copy(); copy.setItemDamage(0); // Resets the item's damage for calculation purposes attackDamage += ForgeHooks.getTotalArmorValue(player); // Example: Apply armor value to damage // You can add more custom calculations here } // Calculate the final damage value float finalDamage = (float) (attackDamage + baseDamage); finalDamage = ForgeHooks.onLivingHurt(player, DamageSource.generic, finalDamage); return finalDamage; } } \`\`\` This example assumes you are calculating the damage for the player entity in your mod. If you want to calculate the damage for a different type of entity, you can adjust the method accordingly. Make sure to replace \`\\"your_modifier_uuid_here\\"\` with the UUID of any modifiers you want to apply to the attack damage attribute. Note that this code only calculates the damage value. If you want to actually deal damage to another entity, you would need to use the \`attackEntityFrom\` method on the target entity, passing the appropriate \`DamageSource\` and damage value."},{"prompt":"what is the baseDamage parameter for?","completion":"The \`baseDamage\` parameter in the \`calculateDamage\` method is a value that represents any additional damage you want to factor into the calculation. This allows you to include custom damage values specific to your mod or game mechanics. For example, let's say you have a system where certain abilities or effects can increase the damage a player deals temporarily. You can pass that additional damage value through the \`baseDamage\` parameter to calculate the final damage. Here's an updated version of the \`calculateDamage\` method with an explanation of the \`baseDamage\` parameter: \`\`\`java import net.minecraft.entity.SharedMonsterAttributes; import net.minecraft.entity.ai.attributes.AttributeModifier; import net.minecraft.entity.player.EntityPlayer; import net.minecraft.entity.player.EntityPlayerMP; import net.minecraft.item.ItemStack; import net.minecraft.util.DamageSource; import net.minecraftforge.common.ForgeHooks; public class MyModDamageUtils { public static float calculateDamage(EntityPlayer player, ItemStack heldItem, float baseDamage) { // Get the player's attack damage attribute double attackDamage = player.getEntityAttribute(SharedMonsterAttributes.attackDamage).getBaseValue(); // Optionally, apply any modifiers to the attack damage attribute attackDamage += player.getEntityAttribute(SharedMonsterAttributes.attackDamage) .getModifier(UUID.fromString(\\"your_modifier_uuid_here\\")).getAmount(); // Apply any additional custom logic or modifiers to the base damage value // Here you can factor in the held item's properties, enchantments, or any other custom calculations // For example, you can check the item's damage, enchantments, or any other properties if (!heldItem.isEmpty()) { ItemStack copy = heldItem.copy(); copy.setItemDamage(0); // Resets the item's damage for calculation purposes attackDamage += ForgeHooks.getTotalArmorValue(player); // Example: Apply armor value to damage // You can add more custom calculations here } // Calculate the final damage value float finalDamage = (float) (attackDamage + baseDamage); finalDamage = ForgeHooks.onLivingHurt(player, DamageSource.generic, finalDamage); return finalDamage; } } \`\`\` In this example, the \`baseDamage\` parameter allows you to include any additional damage values you want to factor into the calculation. For instance, if you have an ability or effect that temporarily increases base damage for a player, you can pass that increased damage value through \`baseDamage\`. This allows you to modify the overall damage calculation without changing the underlying attributes or item values. By incorporating the \`baseDamage\` parameter, you can introduce flexibility and customization to your damage calculation, enabling a more dynamic and diverse gameplay experience in your mod."},{"prompt":"Are there any forseeable downsides to using ForgeHooks.onLivingHurt?","completion":"While I could not find any specific downsides associated with using \`ForgeHooks.onLivingHurt\`, it is important to remember that it is a hook provided by Forge for mods to modify how damage is handled. With that being said, here are a few considerations to keep in mind when using \`ForgeHooks.onLivingHurt\`: 1. Compatibility: Some other mods may also utilize \`ForgeHooks.onLivingHurt\` to modify damage calculations or apply additional effects. This means that if multiple mods are using this hook, the order in which they are called may impact the final damage value. Mod conflicts or unintended interactions can arise if conflicting mods modify damage in inconsistent ways. 2. Consistency: Because \`ForgeHooks.onLivingHurt\` allows for modification of damage values, it can introduce variability in how damage is dealt. This may lead to gameplay experiences that feel inconsistent or unpredictable, potentially affecting balance and player expectations. 3. Documentation and Support: The \`ForgeHooks\` class and its associated methods may not always be well-documented or explained thoroughly. Therefore, it may be more challenging to troubleshoot issues or seek support if you encounter unexpected behavior or conflicts. 4. Modder Responsibility: When using hooks provided by Forge or other mods, it is important to understand their intended usage and potential implications. Carefully consider how modifications to damage calculations impact your gameplay mechanics and ensure that you are providing a consistent and balanced experience for players. It is always a good practice to thoroughly test and assess the impact of using hooks like \`ForgeHooks.onLivingHurt\` in your specific mod environment. Monitor for mod conflicts, unexpected behavior, and ensure that the overall gameplay experience remains balanced and enjoyable. Remember to keep your mod up-to-date and be prepared to make adjustments as needed to address any changes or conflicts that may arise with future updates to Minecraft Forge or other mods."},{"prompt":"Looking more closely, I see your code uses the player's armor to increase the player's attack value. Is this how vanilla does it?","completion":"Apologies for any confusion caused by my previous response. Upon further review, I realize that the code snippet doesn't accurately represent how vanilla Minecraft handles damage calculations with armor. In vanilla Minecraft, the player's attack value is not directly affected by their armor. The player's attack damage is determined by various factors, including the weapon they are wielding, any enchantments on the weapon, and the base attack damage attribute of the player entity. To calculate the final attack damage in a manner consistent with vanilla, you could modify the code to exclude the armor calculation. Here's an updated version of the \`calculateDamage\` method reflecting this adjustment: \`\`\`java import net.minecraft.entity.SharedMonsterAttributes; import net.minecraft.entity.ai.attributes.AttributeModifier; import net.minecraft.entity.player.EntityPlayer; import net.minecraft.entity.player.EntityPlayerMP; import net.minecraft.item.ItemStack; import net.minecraft.util.DamageSource; import net.minecraftforge.common.ForgeHooks; public class MyModDamageUtils { public static float calculateDamage(EntityPlayer player, ItemStack heldItem, float baseDamage) { // Get the player's attack damage attribute double attackDamage = player.getEntityAttribute(SharedMonsterAttributes.attackDamage).getBaseValue(); // Optionally, apply any modifiers to the attack damage attribute attackDamage += player.getEntityAttribute(SharedMonsterAttributes.attackDamage) .getModifier(UUID.fromString(\\"your_modifier_uuid_here\\")).getAmount(); // Apply any additional custom logic or modifiers to the base damage value // Here you can factor in the held item's properties, enchantments, or any other custom calculations // For example, you can check the item's damage, enchantments, or any other properties if (!heldItem.isEmpty()) { ItemStack copy = heldItem.copy(); copy.setItemDamage(0); // Resets the item's damage for calculation purposes // You can add more custom calculations here } // Calculate the final damage value float finalDamage = (float) (attackDamage + baseDamage); finalDamage = ForgeHooks.onLivingHurt(player, DamageSource.generic, finalDamage); return finalDamage; } } \`\`\` By removing the armor calculation and only considering the player's attack damage attribute and any additional custom logic, the code now aligns more closely with vanilla Minecraft's approach to calculating attack damage. Remember to adjust the code as needed based on your specific requirements and intended gameplay mechanics."},{"prompt":"write email please asking for leave requst","completion":"Subject: Leave Request Dear [Manager/Supervisor's Name], I hope this email finds you well. I am writing to formally request a leave of absence from [start date] to [end date]. The reason for this leave request is [mention the reason here, such as a personal commitment, family obligation, medical appointment, or any other legitimate reason]. During my absence, I will ensure that my work is completed or adequately delegated to a trusted colleague to ensure uninterrupted workflow. I have already checked the department calendar and verified that my selected dates do not conflict with any major deadlines or company events. I will also make sure to inform my colleagues about my upcoming leave well in advance, so they can plan their tasks accordingly. I understand that my absence may cause temporary inconvenience to the team or project, and I apologize for any disruption this may cause. However, I assure you that I will make myself available remotely, to the extent possible, to address any urgent matters or provide guidance if needed. I have attached a completed leave application form to this email, as required. Kindly review it and let me know if any additional documentation or information is needed from my end to process this request smoothly. I kindly request your understanding and approval for this leave. Your support in this matter would be greatly appreciated. If there is anything I can do to assist during my absence or if you require further details, please do not hesitate to reach out to me. Thank you for your attention to this matter. I look forward to your response. Yours sincerely, [Your Name] [Your Designation/Job Title] [Your Contact Information]"},{"prompt":"Write a news report about the UK introducing it's own version of No Child Left Behind","completion":"Title: UK Introduces Ambitious 'Education for All' Program, Inspired by No Child Left Behind Date: [Insert Date] In a bid to revolutionize its education system and ensure no student is left behind, the United Kingdom has unveiled a new and ambitious education initiative, drawing inspiration from the highly debated No Child Left Behind Act implemented in the United States. Dubbed 'Education for All,' the UK's version aims to address academic disparities, improve student outcomes, and enhance educational opportunities for every child in the country. Recognizing the need for massive reforms to bridge the achievement gap, policymakers have embarked on an ambitious journey to transform the nation's education landscape. Education Secretary [Insert Name] announced the initiative during a press conference, stressing the importance of providing quality education for all students, regardless of their background or circumstances. Developed after extensive research and consultation with educational experts, 'Education for All' puts an emphasis on a comprehensive approach to ensure every child receives the support and resources they need to succeed academically. One of the central pillars of the program is the establishment of stricter accountability measures. This involves setting specific targets for schools across the country, with a focus on student achievement, standardized test scores, and graduation rates. Schools failing to meet these targets will receive additional resources and support to help them improve, while consistently underperforming institutions may face interventions or potential restructuring. A key aspect of the initiative is early identification and intervention. Under 'Education for All,' schools will be required to identify struggling students early on and provide them with targeted support to accelerate their learning. This will be achieved through a range of measures, including additional tutoring, personalized learning plans, and enhanced teacher training to address specific areas of difficulty. To alleviate the burden on schools and ensure equitable access to resources, the UK government has promised significant investment in education, including improved facilities, increased staffing, and enhanced training opportunities for teachers. The government will work closely with local authorities and education boards to allocate resources fairly and effectively, ensuring no region is left behind. While the move has been widely lauded as a much-needed step towards improving educational outcomes, it has not been without its critics. Some skeptics argue that such ambitious initiatives can lead to an excessive focus on testing and neglect the broader aspects of a well-rounded education. Others call for more investment in early childhood education and extracurricular activities to complement the academic aims of the program. Nonetheless, 'Education for All' marks a significant milestone in the revitalization of the UK's education system. With its focus on accountability, early intervention, and equitable distribution of resources, the initiative aims to reshape the educational landscape and ensure that every child in the country is presented with equal opportunities to reach their full potential. As the program begins its implementation, educators and parents eagerly await the transformative effects it may have on the lives of students across the nation. Only time will tell whether the UK's version of No Child Left Behind will succeed in its ambitious goals, but its dedication to inclusive education is a promising step towards a brighter future."},{"prompt":"Write another report where Coca Cola reintroduces New Coke","completion":"Title: Coca-Cola Stirs Nostalgia, Reintroduces New Coke in Surprise Move Date: [Insert Date] In a surprising move that has left consumers buzzing with nostalgia, Coca-Cola, the iconic beverage giant, has announced the re-release of New Coke, a beverage that was met with mixed reactions and quickly withdrawn from the market over three decades ago. The decision to revisit New Coke was driven by a desire to tap into the current trend of revived retro offerings. Nostalgia has gained significant traction in the marketplace, with consumers craving the tastes and experiences of yesteryears. Coca-Cola, renowned for its mastery of marketing and consumer engagement, aims to capitalize on this nostalgia wave. Originally launched in 1985, New Coke was intended to replace the beloved original formula, prompting an intense backlash from loyal Coca-Cola fans who felt betrayed by the change. The outcry was so fervent that three months later, Coca-Cola reintroduced the classic formulation as Coca-Cola Classic, which ultimately dominated sales, relegating New Coke to obscurity. However, looking to rewrite the narrative surrounding New Coke, Coca-Cola is reintroducing the beverage as a limited-time offering, embracing its historical significance and catering to those curious enough to try it for the first time or revisit it. Company executives remain adamant that this move is not about altering the immensely successful Coca-Cola Classic formula but rather about indulging their customers' sense of nostalgia and providing an opportunity for personal memories and cultural milestones to resurface. The relaunch of New Coke has sparked debate among industry experts and consumers alike. While some argue that this is a savvy marketing move and an innovative way to leverage nostalgia, others express skepticism, questioning whether consumers truly want a taste of the past or are simply content with the original Coca-Cola experience. Coca-Cola's strategy involves engaging consumers in the narrative surrounding New Coke. The company plans to roll out a series of promotional activities, including limited-edition packaging featuring retro designs and exclusive collaborations with influential celebrities and social media influencers who will share their personal experiences and thoughts about the beverage. Critics argue that Coca-Cola should focus on innovation rather than relying on repackaging old ideas. They contend that the company's efforts should be directed towards addressing shifting consumer demands, such as sugar reduction, eco-friendly packaging, and healthier beverage alternatives. Nonetheless, Coca-Cola is confident in the potential of New Coke's resurgence. The beverage giant hopes the reintroduction will capitalize on the deep emotional connection that consumers have with their brand, sparking conversations and garnering interest among both loyalists and adventurous newcomers. As the battle for consumer attention and loyalty intensifies, Coca-Cola's decision to bring back New Coke serves as a reminder that iconic brands must evolve and adapt, while also embracing their rich heritage. Only time will tell whether this nostalgic voyage will be a triumphant comeback for New Coke or a short-lived experiment that keeps us pining for the classic formulation."},{"prompt":"Translate this JSON RFC8259 format from english to thailand language. DO NOT translate the key, only provide a RFC8259 compliant JSON response { “nav1”:“Overview”, “nav2”:“Flash News”, “nav3”:“Research”, “nav4”:“Academy”, “nav5”:“Column”, “nav6”:“Community Index”, “nav7”:“Launch Space”, “USER_TOOLTIP”:“My Account”, “LOGIN”:“Login”, “LOGOUT”:“Logout”, “HOME_PAGE”:“Home Page”, “REGISTER”:“Register”, “USERNAME”:“Username”, “EMAIL”:“Email”, “PASSWORD”:“Password”, “CONFIRM_PASSWORD”:“Confirm Password”, “PASSWORD_HELPER_TEXT”:“At least 8-15 digits, including digits and alphabets.”, “NEW_ACCOUNT?”:\\"Have you created an account yet? \\", “REGISTER_NOW”:“Register Now”, “REGISTERED_SUCCESSFULLY”:“Registered Successfully”, “ACCOUNT_ACTIVATION_MESSAGE”:“Go to your email to activate your account and explore the world of blockchain today”, “EMAIL_VERIFICATION_MESSAGE_1”:“We have sent a verification link to the following email address.”, “EMAIL_VERIFICATION_MESSAGE_2”:“Didn’t get the verification link? Try sending the verification link again.”, “SEND_LINK_AGAIN”:“Send verification link again”, “PLEASE_WAIT”:“Please Wait”, “EMAIL_SUCCESS_MESSAGE”:“Successfully sent verification link!”, “SECONDS”:“Seconds”, “LOGIN_TO”:“Login To”, “NEW_USER_REGISTRATION”:“New User Registration”, “INVITATION_CODE”:“Invitation code”, “OPTIONAL”:“Optional”, “DISCLAIMER_TEXT_1”:\\"Please read these \\", “